        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "MOTIVATION ",
        "text_level": 1,
        "bbox": [
            8,
            167,
            78,
            191
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "OUR APPROACH",
        "text_level": 1,
        "bbox": [
            257,
            167,
            345,
            191
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "RESULTS ",
        "text_level": 1,
        "bbox": [
            629,
            168,
            679,
            191
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Scale Equivariance: ",
        "text_level": 1,
        "bbox": [
            8,
            201,
            84,
            222
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "image",
        "img_path": "/data/huangyc/Document2All/posterDataOutput_vlm/Truly Scale-Equivariant Deep Nets with Fourier Layers_poster/auto/images/images/fig_1.jpg",
        "image_caption": [],
        "image_footnote": [],
        "bbox": [
            15,
            223,
            233,
            370
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "·Scale-equivariance is crucial for consistent performance ·Prior works did not consider aliasing,resulting in equivariance error ",
        "bbox": [
            22,
            387,
            244,
            453
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Can we design a perfect scale equivariant layer? ",
        "text_level": 1,
        "bbox": [
            13,
            462,
            188,
            481
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "· Maintain scale consistency while achieving good performance ",
        "bbox": [
            14,
            483,
            244,
            504
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Contributions: ",
        "text_level": 1,
        "bbox": [
            9,
            509,
            65,
            527
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "·Propose scale-equivariant Fourier Layer · End-to-end equivariance with non-linearity and pooling · Connect scale equivariance to classification task for improved scale consistency. ",
        "bbox": [
            22,
            529,
            244,
            618
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "INTRODUCTION ",
        "text_level": 1,
        "bbox": [
            8,
            644,
            92,
            668
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Scaling Operation: Down-scaling a signal $\\mathbf { x } ~ \\in ~ \\mathbb { R } ^ { N } \\mathrm { c a n }$ be performed by subsampling by a scaling factor,i.e., ",
        "bbox": [
            8,
            679,
            245,
            723
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "img_path": "/data/huangyc/Document2All/posterDataOutput_vlm/Truly Scale-Equivariant Deep Nets with Fourier Layers_poster/auto/images/equations/equations_1.jpg",
        "text": "$$\n\\mathtt { S u b } _ { R } ( { \\bf x } ) [ n ] = { \\bf x } [ R n ] .\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            87,
            731,
            166,
            756
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Ideal Down-sampling: To avoid aliasing from subsampling,a lowpass filter $h$ must be performed,i.e., ",
        "bbox": [
            7,
            764,
            246,
            808
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "img_path": "/data/huangyc/Document2All/posterDataOutput_vlm/Truly Scale-Equivariant Deep Nets with Fourier Layers_poster/auto/images/equations/equations_2.jpg",
        "text": "$$\n\\mathcal { D } _ { R } ( \\mathbf { x } ) = \\mathtt { S u b } _ { R } ( \\mathbf { h } \\circledast \\mathbf { x } ) .\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            82,
            815,
            170,
            840
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "image",
        "img_path": "/data/huangyc/Document2All/posterDataOutput_vlm/Truly Scale-Equivariant Deep Nets with Fourier Layers_poster/auto/images/images/fig_2.jpg",
        "image_caption": [],
        "image_footnote": [],
        "bbox": [
            13,
            852,
            237,
            983
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Scale Equivariant Deep Nets ",
        "text_level": 1,
        "bbox": [
            269,
            207,
            377,
            228
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Let $g$ denote a deep net such that $\\mathbf { y } = g ( \\mathbf { x } )$ . If this deep net $g$ can be equivalently represented as a set of functions $\\dot { \\tilde { G } } _ { k } : \\mathbb { C } ^ { 2 k + 1 }  \\dot { \\mathbb { C } }$ such that ",
        "bbox": [
            267,
            235,
            606,
            278
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "img_path": "/data/huangyc/Document2All/posterDataOutput_vlm/Truly Scale-Equivariant Deep Nets with Fourier Layers_poster/auto/images/equations/equations_3.jpg",
        "text": "$$\n{ \\bf Y } [ k ] = \\tilde { G } _ { k } ( { \\bf X } [ - k : k ] ) \\ \\forall k\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            387,
            291,
            487,
            319
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "then $g$ is scale-equivariant. In other words, the output’s frequency terms can only depend on the terms in $\\mathbf { X }$ that are equal or lower in frequencies. We illustrate this structure with a linear function, $\\tilde { G }$ , in the Figure. The values of the Grey cells are 0. ",
        "bbox": [
            268,
            335,
            606,
            399
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "image",
        "img_path": "/data/huangyc/Document2All/posterDataOutput_vlm/Truly Scale-Equivariant Deep Nets with Fourier Layers_poster/auto/images/images/fig_3.jpg",
        "image_caption": [],
        "image_footnote": [],
        "bbox": [
            271,
            425,
            405,
            600
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Spatially Localized Spectral Conv: ",
        "text_level": 1,
        "bbox": [
            432,
            434,
            562,
            454
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "· $\\checkmark$ Spectral convolution is scale equivariant   \n· $\\boldsymbol { \\cal X }$ Global in nature-ill fit for vision tasks   \n·We propose Localized Spectral Convolution $\\checkmark$ Maintains equivariance $\\checkmark$ Captures local features ",
        "bbox": [
            446,
            456,
            608,
            564
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Non-Linearity and Pooling: ",
        "text_level": 1,
        "bbox": [
            437,
            587,
            540,
            606
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "·For any function $\\sigma$ ,its scale equivariant version, $\\sigma _ { e q } ( { \\bf x } ) = { \\bf y }$ ,can be defined as ",
        "bbox": [
            450,
            608,
            616,
            649
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "image",
        "img_path": "/data/huangyc/Document2All/posterDataOutput_vlm/Truly Scale-Equivariant Deep Nets with Fourier Layers_poster/auto/images/images/fig_4.jpg",
        "image_caption": [],
        "image_footnote": [],
        "bbox": [
            258,
            604,
            434,
            947
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "$\\mathbf { Y } [ k ] = { \\mathcal { F } } { \\Big ( } { \\boldsymbol { \\sigma } } \\circ { \\mathcal { F } } ^ { - 1 } ( \\mathbf { X } { \\big [ } - | k | : | k | { \\big ] } ) { \\Big ) } [ k ]$ where $\\mathbf { X } = { \\mathcal { F } } ( \\mathbf { x } )$ and $\\mathbf { Y } = { \\mathcal { F } } ( \\mathbf { y } )$ ",
        "bbox": [
            457,
            654,
            612,
            730
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Classification and Scaling: ",
        "text_level": 1,
        "bbox": [
            433,
            756,
            531,
            776
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "· Invariance is not desirable for scaling ·Classification loss should not increase at a higher scale · We propose scale consistency loss ",
        "bbox": [
            446,
            779,
            614,
            867
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "equation",
        "img_path": "/data/huangyc/Document2All/posterDataOutput_vlm/Truly Scale-Equivariant Deep Nets with Fourier Layers_poster/auto/images/equations/equations_4.jpg",
        "text": "$$\n\\mathcal { L } _ { c o n } = \\operatorname* { m a x } \\mathopen { } \\mathclose \\bgroup \\left( \\mathcal { L } ( \\hat { \\pmb { y } } [ k ] , y ) - \\mathcal { L } ( \\hat { \\pmb { y } } [ k - 1 ] , y ) , 0 \\aftergroup \\egroup \\right) .\n$$",
        "text_format": "latex",
        "bbox": [
            453,
            880,
            613,
            907
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Here, $\\hat { y } [ k ]$ is the prediction of classifier $\\mathcal { M }$ at $k ^ { \\mathrm { t h } }$ scale. ",
        "bbox": [
            454,
            921,
            615,
            963
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
    {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Qualitative Results:Perfect scale equivalence with non-linearity and pooling (Left)．Robust to non-ideal down-sampling (Right). ",
        "bbox": [
            629,
            201,
            991,
            243
        ],
        "page_idx": 0
    },
